The purpurae seem to have been purple togas. It is clear that such things were worn, for Augustus as early as 13.c. 36 (Dion Cassius xmx. 16) issued a decree that none but magistrates and senators should wear them. It is possible, however, that the purpurae are only the fringe of the toga praetexta, worn by all curule magistrates.
